=========================================
C++17 std::string_view
INTERVIEW NOTES
=========================================

1. What is std::string_view?

std::string_view is a C++17 lightweight, non-owning view of a string.

It does NOT own the string data.
It only provides a window (view) into existing string memory.

Header

#include <string_view>

Syntax

std::string_view

-----------------------------------------

2. Why was std::string_view introduced?

Before C++

void print(const string& s)
{
    cout << s;
}

Problem:

Even when you pass:

• string literal
• substring
• temporary string

you often end up with unnecessary copies or constraints.

Also:

• std::string is heavy (memory allocation possible)
• copying strings is expensive

-----------------------------------------

3. C++17 Solution

#include <string_view>
using namespace std;

void print(string_view s)
{
    cout << s;
}

Now you can pass:

• std::string
• string literal
• substring
• char arrays

All without copying.

-----------------------------------------

4. Example

#include <iostream>
#include <string_view>
using namespace std;

void print(string_view s)
{
    cout << s << endl;
}

int main()
{
    string str = "Hello";
    print(str);              // string
    print("World");          // string literal
    print(string("Hi"));    // temporary string
}

Output

Hello
World
Hi

-----------------------------------------

5. Key Feature

std::string_view does NOT copy data.

It stores only:

• pointer to string data
• length

Internally:

struct string_view
{
    const char* ptr;
    size_t size;
};

-----------------------------------------

6. Why is it fast?

Because:

• No memory allocation
• No string copying
• Only pointer + size

-----------------------------------------

7. Important Warning ⚠️ (VERY IMPORTANT INTERVIEW POINT)

string_view does NOT own memory.

So this is dangerous:

string_view sv;

{
    string s = "Hello";
    sv = s;
}

Now s is destroyed → sv becomes dangling → Undefined Behavior

-----------------------------------------

8. Safe usage rules

✔ Use with:

• string literals
• long-lived strings
• function parameters

❌ Avoid:

• returning string_view to local string
• storing string_view beyond lifetime of original string

-----------------------------------------

9. Substring without copying

string str = "HelloWorld";

string_view sv(str);

cout << sv.substr(0,5);

Output

Hello

No new string is created.

-----------------------------------------

10. Common Methods

size()

cout << sv.size();

data()

const char* p = sv.data();

substr()

auto sub = sv.substr(2,3);

remove_prefix()

sv.remove_prefix(2);

remove_suffix()

sv.remove_suffix(2);

-----------------------------------------

11. Difference: string vs string_view

std::string

• Owns memory
• Copy is expensive
• Can modify

std::string_view

• Does NOT own memory
• Very fast
• Read-only view

-----------------------------------------

12. When to use string_view?

Best use cases:

• function parameters
• logging systems
• parsing
• read-only string processing
• APIs needing high performance

-----------------------------------------

13. Example of optimization

Before

void log(const string& s)
{
    cout << s;
}

C++17

void log(string_view s)
{
    cout << s;
}

Now accepts:

• string
• "literal"
• substring

without overhead

-----------------------------------------

14. Interview Questions

Q. What is std::string_view?

Answer

std::string_view is a C++17 non-owning reference to a string that provides a lightweight view without copying or allocating memory.

-----------------------------------------

Q. Which C++ version introduced string_view?

Answer

C++17

-----------------------------------------

Q. What problem does it solve?

Answer

It avoids unnecessary copying of strings and allocations by providing a lightweight view instead of owning string data.

-----------------------------------------

Q. Does string_view own memory?

Answer

No. It only references existing string data.

-----------------------------------------

Q. What is the risk of string_view?

Answer

If the original string goes out of scope, string_view becomes dangling and leads to undefined behavior.

-----------------------------------------

Q. Difference between string and string_view?

Answer

string owns memory and allows modifications, while string_view is a non-owning, read-only view with no memory allocation.

-----------------------------------------

Q. Can string_view modify data?

Answer

No. It is read-only.

-----------------------------------------

15. Interview Explanation (30 seconds)

"std::string_view is a C++17 feature that provides a non-owning, lightweight view of a string. Unlike std::string, 
it does not allocate memory or copy data; it only stores a pointer and length. This makes it very efficient for 
function parameters and read-only string operations. However, it must be used carefully because it does not own the 
underlying data, so dangling references can occur if the original string is destroyed."

